The paper deals with querying spatial data sets efficiently, which is a common topic in computer science. The use of probabilistic neighborhoods is a novel approach to this problem, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. However, the paper also presents a fast algorithm for sampling probabilistic neighborhoods from planar point sets, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the simulation of probabilistic spreading phenomena, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on spatial data sets and distance metrics suggests that it may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DB (Databases) sub-categories.
